[Patient] How much fluid should I drink daily to manage my heart failure?
[Healthcare Educator] Aim for about 8 cups (64 ounces) of fluids per day, but listen to your body's needs.
[Patient] Can I drink any type of fluid, or are there restrictions?
[Healthcare Educator] Focus on water, herbal teas, and low-sodium broths. Limit sugary drinks and alcohol.
[Patient] What signs should I look out for to know if I'm retaining too much fluid?
[Healthcare Educator] Watch for sudden weight gain, swelling in your legs or abdomen, and difficulty breathing.
[Patient] How can I track my fluid intake throughout the day?
[Healthcare Educator] Use a water bottle to measure how much you drink. Consider keeping a fluid intake journal.
[Patient] Are there any foods that can help me stay hydrated and manage my heart failure?
[Healthcare Educator] Include fruits like watermelon, oranges, and cucumbers in your diet. They can help with hydration.